WHAT MAKE PEOPLE HAPPY?¶

Studying happiness could help doctors improve their therapies, assist teachers to improve their teaching techniques, and help companies to put forward a better sales plan. In this project, I will analyze HappyDB data to obtain the things that can make most people feel happy in our daily life.

I. Wordcloud¶

Wordcloud is a way to show the frequencies or importances of text through vivid graph. In the graph, we can analyze the frequency of a word by its size. In this part, I will compare results of the original data with results of the processed data to see if there is any difference between them and to determine which one is more reasonable.

II.CountVectorizer & TfidVectorizer¶

CountVectorizer can count frequencies of each words in this text, while TfidVectorizer take the words' frequencies in the corpus into consideration.

iii. textRank¶

TextRank is a method that learns the relationships between words, and then after calculation, it can get the importance of words. In this part, I will use textRank to get the most important words in our data set.

In [13]:
def buildG(text):
    
    G = nx.Graph()
    
    word2id = {}
    id2word = {}
    for sentence in text:
        try:
            tokens = sentence.split()
        except:
            print(tokens)
            continue
        length = len(tokens)
        if len(tokens)>1:
            for i in range(0, length-1):
                w1 = tokens[i]
                
                if w1 in word2id:
                    w1_idx = word2id[w1]
                else:
                    w1_idx = len(word2id)
                    word2id[w1] = w1_idx
                    id2word[w1_idx] = w1
                    G.add_node(w1_idx)
            
                for j in range(i+1, length):
                    w2 = tokens[j]
                    if w2 in word2id:
                        w2_idx = word2id[w2]
                    else:
                        w2_idx = len(word2id)
                        word2id[w2] = w2_idx
                        id2word[w2_idx] = w2
                        G.add_node(w2_idx)
                    
                    if not G.has_edge(w1_idx, w2_idx):
                        G.add_edge(w1_idx, w2_idx, weights=1)
                    else:
                        G[w1_idx][w2_idx]['weights'] += 1
    return G, word2id, id2word

iv. lda¶

Lda is a generative probability model that can discover themes in text and give latent topics along with potential keywords.

In [17]:
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline
from sklearn.decomposition import LatentDirichletAllocation as lda
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
In [18]:
pipeline = Pipeline([
    ("countvectorizor", CountVectorizer(min_df=10)),
    ("lda", lda(max_iter=20, learning_method='batch'))
])

param_grid = {'lda__n_components': [9,12]}


cv = GridSearchCV(pipeline, 
                  param_grid, 
                  cv=3,
                  n_jobs=4)

Since unproper text length has lots of disadvantages to our analysis (Hong and Davison 2010), so we set minimum and maximum length to avoid data noise.

In [19]:
min_words = 20

    (happy_df_proc.text.str.len()>min_words) &
    (happy_df_proc.text.str.len()<max_words)
]
print("Text more than {} words less than {} words: {}\n".format(min_words, 
                                                                max_words,

t1 = time.time()
cv.fit(lda_text.text)
t2 = time.time()

In [20]:
def print_top_words(model, feature_names, n_top_words):
    for topic_idx, topic in enumerate(model.components_):
        message = "Topic #%d: " % topic_idx
        message += " ".join([feature_names[i]
                             for i in topic.argsort()[:-n_top_words - 1:-1]])
        print(message)
    print()

From the above plot, we can get word length distribution across different category. Enjoy the moment has the most words, while exercise has the least words. In other words, people tend to use more words to describe the way they enjoy the moment, while they use short words to describe exercise.

vi. Overview¶

In conclusion, it is importent to learn happy moment in our daily life. For most people, their happy moments are related to friends, family, love and their job. They enjoy their time when they are relaxing or when they have some achievements in their jobs. The research to happy moments can have lots of applications in our life.
